Visa Lifts View After Q3 Beat; Capital One, E-Trade Jump; Skechers Falls 






APARNA NARAYANAN
7/20/2017


 Reprints




Visa (V),Â E-Trade Financial (ETFC) andÂ Capital One Financial (COF) topped quarterly estimates whileÂ Skechers (SKX) turned in mixed resultsÂ after Thursday's market close.
XAutoplay: On | OffVisa, E-Trade and Capital One are financials, with Visa and Capital One being two card plays, as a slew of payment stocks have broken out in recent weeks, including Mastercard (MA) and American Express (AXP). Shares of Visa and E-Trade Financial are in buy zones ahead of their earnings.
Visa
Estimates: Fiscal Q3 EPS is seen climbing 16% to 80 cents, as revenue jumps 20% to $4.36 billion.
Results: EPS of 86 cents on revenue of $4.6 billion.Â Payments volume growth, on a constant dollar basis, surged 38% to $1.9 trillion.Â Total Visa processed transactions jumped 44% to 28.5 billion, or 13% inclusive of Europe.
Outlook: Full-year revenue growth now seen at 20%, up from a prior view of 16%-18% growth, while Wall Street sees an increase of 18.5%.
Stock: Visa rallied 1.2% late. Shares closedÂ down 0.1% at 98.11 on the stock market today. Visa cleared a 96.70 flat-base buy point last Friday, but the volume on the breakout and this week has not been impressive.
Transaction-services provider Alliance Data Systems (ADS) plunged 9.3% to 239Â after its earnings report this morning. Alliance Data, which handles store credit cards for many merchants, had been flirting near a buy point.
Capital One
Estimates: AnÂ 8% earnings jump to $1.90Â on an almost 7%Â revenue gain to $6.68 billion.
Results:Â EPS of $1.96 on revenue of $6.7 billion. Credit card revenue grew 6.8% to $4.17 billion. Consumer banking revenue rose 9.1% to $1.76 billion, and commercial banking revenue gained 9.3% to $752 million. The provision for credit losses decreased 10% toÂ $1.8 billion.Â Net interest margin was flat at 6.88%.
Stock: Capital One jumped 4.9% late. SharesÂ dipped 0.45% to finish at 81.01, testing support at the 50-day moving average.
E-Trade
Estimates: EPS toÂ stay flat at 48 cents, as revenue jumps nearly 17% to $554 million.
Results: EPS of 52 cents on revenue of $577 million.Â Net new brokerage accounts grew at an annualized pace of 4.7% to 41,000.Â Net new brokerage assets rose at an annualized rate of 3.5% to $2.6 billion.
Stock: E-Trade rose 3.5% late. Shares slipped 0.2% to close at 39.60, but still above a 38.71 entry.
Discount brokerÂ TD Ameritrade (AMTD) reported earlier this week and beat on both the top and bottom lines, despite the industrywide slashing of stock and ETF trading fees. Meanwhile, Charles Schwab (SCHW) met profit views on Tuesday.
Skechers
Estimates: EPSÂ to fall 8% to 44 centsÂ despite a 10%Â revenue jump to $966 million.
Results:Â EPS of 38 cents on net salesÂ of $1.03 billion.Â Domestic wholesale business sales increased 6.4%, international wholesale business sales surged 18.6%, and company-owned global retail business sales jumpedÂ 28%, including a 7.1% gain inÂ Â comparable-store sales.
Stock: Skechers fell 2.3% late. SharesÂ ended 0.9% lower at 28.31.
"Given the increases in our international business, which for the first six months represented 48 percent of our total business, we believe the greatest opportunity for expansion is internationally, and we are investing in our infrastructure and marketing to support this progress," said COO and CFOÂ David Weinberg in a statement.
