These 2 Dow Stocks Are In Buy Zones Ahead Of Earnings 






BILL PETERS
7/17/2017


 Reprints




Dow Jones industrial average componentsÂ American Express (AXP) andÂ Visa (V) report quarterly earnings on Wednesday and Thursday, respectively.
XAutoplay: On | OffMeanwhile, Capital One Financial (COF) andÂ Alliance Data Systems (ADS) report on Thursday.
The results come as shares of those credit card giants and others in the payments spaceÂ flirt with buy zones.
Here's a look at what to expect:
Visa
Estimates:Â Fiscal third-quarter earnings per share of 81 cents, a 17% increase, on revenue of $4.361 billion, a 20% jump, according to Zacks Investment Research.
Stock: Visa cleared a 96.70 flat-base buy point on Friday, hitting a record high and closing at 96.93.
Shares edged down 0.1% to 96.83 MondayÂ stock market trading. Rival Mastercard (MA), which reports second-quarter earnings on July 27, was holding above 126.29 buy point, dipping rising 0.3% to 127.42. Mastercard also broke out of a flat base on Friday.



Even though weak loan growth in a cautious business environment, a tamer forecast for net interest income, and JPMorgan Chase (JPM) CEO Jamie Dimon's rant about "the stupid s**t we have to deal with in this country" became the main take-aways from JPMorgan'sÂ second-quarter earnings on Friday, the bank's credit card sales volumes remained solid. That figure roseÂ 15.3% for Q2, better than in Q1.
"We view JPMorgan's results as having positive implications for Visa, as JPM is Visa's largest issuer," Mizuho analyst Thomas McCrohan wrote in a research note on Friday.
And amid a fight between banks for the biggest spenders, JPMorgan CFO Marianne Lake on Friday also said the "extraordinary success" of the bank's Chase Sapphire Reserve card â which carries the Visa label and is jammed with perks intended to draw a Â wealthier, younger consumer â has been a major accelerant in card revenue.
"I always feel compelled to point out that these are extraordinarily good customers," she said. "Their characteristics, their engagement, their spend â these are the customers that everybody wants to acquire. We now have them and we intend to deepen relationships with them."
Visa also stands to benefit from being the sole credit card provider for Costco (COST), a relationship that came at American Express' expense. Its acquisition last year of Visa Europe, growing support of digitalÂ payments and its forays into nations where many people still pay largely in cash are also seen working in the company's favor.
But more exposure internationally means the company's revenues risk taking a hit from a stronger dollar. Rising client incentives also threaten revenue, Zacks said.
Visa and other card investors should pay attention to Bank of America (BAC) earnings Tuesday, for more insight into credit card trends.
American Express
Estimates: Second-quarter EPS is expected to plunge 43% to $1.47, with revenue dipping 1% to $8.154 billion.
Stock: Shares dipped 0.1% to 85.23 on Monday. The stock is still within range of an 82.10 buy point of a flat base cleared nearly a month ago.



American Express' breakup with Costco last year, along with a less-friendly foreign-exchange translation and higher provisions for losses are likely to weigh on revenue and margins this year, Zacks said.
"Costco used to be a major acquisition channel for American Express' U.S. consumer and small business areas," Zacks said. "Though the company replaced all the volume it used to derive through the Costco channel with other proprietary channels and other products, the adverse impact of the loss of the partnership should continue for next few quarters."
But like Visa, AmEx is also poised to grow as more people use electronic payments and as countries outside the U.S. adopt credit cards. The company has also tried to compete with the Chase Sapphire Reserve by adding its own sweeteners to its high-end Platinum Card.
Capital One, Alliance Data Systems
Meanwhile, Capital OneÂ is expected to report an 8% EPS gain to $1.90, with revenue up 6.5% to $6.67 billion. But Capital One has missed earnings estimates in four of the last five quarters, including the last two. Revenue has been below views in the last two quarters. The stock is trading between its 200-day and 50-day moving averages as it tries to build a new base. Capital One stock fellÂ 0.4% Monday.
Alliance Data Systems, which manages private-label credit cards for retailers and other businesses, is slated to boost per-share profit by 6% to $3.47, with revenue up 5% to $1.837 billion. Shares fell 0.9% to 261.85 Monday.Â That stock peeked out past a 264.56 buy pointÂ from a cup-with-handle base on Thursday, then dipped back below that entry on Friday.



